{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17646713","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17646713"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T20:34:42+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T20:34:42+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18202"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18202","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18202"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.16,0.03,0.32,0.24,0.26]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10916"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"73804"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10916","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10916"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18202"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"59279"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4926"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"5220"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"25377"},{"type":"contributions","id":"25379"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"73804","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/73804"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following statements about COX-2 inhibitors and cardiovascular risk is correct?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Celecoxib is safe for patients with cardiovascular disease","Paracoxib has no known cardiovascular risks","Both celecoxib and paracoxib should be avoided in patients with cardiovascular disease","Celecoxib is safer than paracoxib in terms of cardiovascular risk","Paracoxib is safer than celecoxib in terms of cardiovascular risk"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003ECOX-2 inhibitors are a class of drugs used to reduce inflammation and pain. However, they have been associated with certain cardiovascular risks, particularly in patients with pre-existing cardiovascular conditions.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBoth \u003Cstrong\u003Ecelecoxib and paracoxib should be avoided in patients with cardiovascular disease\u003C/strong\u003E due to their association with increased cardiovascular risk. COX-2 inhibitors can lead to an increased risk of heart attack and stroke, particularly in patients with existing cardiovascular conditions.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECelecoxib is safe for patients with cardiovascular disease\u003C/strong\u003E - This is incorrect as celecoxib is associated with increased cardiovascular risk\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EParacoxib has no known cardiovascular risks\u003C/strong\u003E - Paracoxib, like other COX-2 inhibitors, carries cardiovascular risks\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECelecoxib is safer than paracoxib in terms of cardiovascular risk\u003C/strong\u003E - Both drugs have similar cardiovascular risk profiles\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EParacoxib is safer than celecoxib in terms of cardiovascular risk\u003C/strong\u003E - There is no evidence to suggest that paracoxib is safer than celecoxib\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["COX-2 inhibitors, such as celecoxib, are associated with an increased risk of cardiovascular events.","Paracoxib is also a COX-2 inhibitor and shares similar cardiovascular risks with celecoxib.","Patients with pre-existing cardiovascular disease should avoid COX-2 inhibitors due to their potential to increase cardiovascular risk."],"references":["Waller, D. G., \u0026 Hitchings, A. W. (2021). Medical Pharmacology and Therapeutics E-Book: Medical Pharmacology and Therapeutics E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Tashjian, A. H., \u0026 Armstrong, E. J. (2011). Principles of pharmacology: the pathophysiologic basis of drug therapy. Lippincott Williams \u0026 Wilkins","Queremel Milani DA, Davis DD. Pain Management Medications. 2023 Jul 3. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 32809527","Carter GT, Duong V, Ho S, Ngo KC, Greer CL, Weeks DL. Side effects of commonly prescribed analgesic medications. Phys Med Rehabil Clin N Am. 2014 May;25(2):457-70. doi: 10.1016/j.pmr.2014.01.007. PMID: 24787343","Qureshi O, Dua A. COX Inhibitors. 2024 Feb 28. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 31747202"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"59279"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18202"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"59279","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/59279"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-24T04:27:05+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-24T04:27:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10916"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"73804"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a juni